article.headline: Washington 63, Arizona State 55
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Giuliana Mendiola is moving up the all-time
Washington scoring list and bringing her teammates along too.

Mendiola scored 31 points Thursday night to lead Washington over
Arizona State 63-55.

In making four late free throws, Mendiola pulled Washington
(16-10, 9-8 Pac-10) ahead for good with just under three minutes to
play. She finished the game 16-of-20 from the line.

Mendiola, who scored 20-plus points for the 15th time this
season, moved past Rhonda Smith (1992-95) in UW career scoring with
1,805 points, four more than Smith. Jamie Redd (1996-99) holds the
school record with 2,027 points.

The Sun Devils (17-9, 11-6) fought back, pulling to within one
point, 50-49, but poor shooting and foul trouble down the stretch
sealed the Washington win.

"This was a hard-fought game," Washington coach June Daugherty
said. "Tough game by both teams."

Andrea Lalum had 15 points and Cameo Hicks added nine for the
Huskies.

"We just got the ball inside more in the second half and made
our free throws," Lalum said.

Kylan Loney led the Sun Devils with 12 points and five assists.

The Huskies are 15-3 against the Sun Devils in Seattle,
including six victories in a row. The last Arizona State win was
Feb. 3, 1996.

"I'm proud of our defense, holding them to 55," Daugherty
said. "(Kristen) Kovesdy had 29 against us last time, so holding
her to just two is huge."

Arizona State's Emily Westerberg left the game at the 17:42 mark
of the second half when she appeared to sprain her left ankle. She
had four points.

A long three-pointer from Loney gave the Sun Devils a 32-26
halftime lead.

After the final buzzer, Loney was seen leaving the court holding
her face. Daugherty said one of the Washington players "went to
high-five her, and missed." Sun Devils head coach Charli Turner
didn't speak to reporters after the game.
